Plants possess various defense mechanisms to prevent pathogen infection, including phytoalexin accumulation. Phytoalexins are defined as low molecular weight anti-microbial compounds produced by plants in response to pathogen infection, which provide an inducible chemical barrier against pathogen attacks. The significance of phytoalexin accumulation in the interaction of plants with pathogenic microorganisms has been demonstrated experimentally. For example, incompatible combinations of oat (

Avena sativa

) cultivars and crown rust fungus (

Puccinia coronata

f. sp. 
avenae
) races were found to induce the accumulation of phytoalexins at high concentrations (

). Plants without the ability to produce phytoalexins were shown to be more susceptible to pathogenic infection compared with phytoalexin-producing wild 
type
plants in 

Arabidopsis thaliana
(
Thomma et al., 1999
)

. The genetically modified tobacco (

Nicotiana tabacum

) plant that accumulates a foreign phytoalexin, resveratrol, showed enhanced resistance to pathogens (

). Moreover, tolerance to phytoalexins, due to their degradation and exclusion, has been identified as a factor of virulence by pathogenic microorganisms (

).

            Poaceae
species accumulate phytoalexins with diverse chemical structures, including phenylamides, flavonoids, and terpenoids. For example, rice (

Oryza sativa

) plants accumulate 19 phytoalexins; 14 labdane-related diterpenes (momilactones, oryzalexins, and phytocassanes), one casbene-type diterpene (
ent
-10-oxodepressin), one flavanone (sakuranetin), and two phenylamides (
N
-benzoyltryptamine and 
N
-cinnamoyltryptamine) (

,b; 

; 

; 

). In maize (

Zea mays

), the diterpenoids kauralexins and dolabralexins (

; 

) and sesquiterpenoid zealexins were identified as phytoalexins (

). In oats, avenanthramide phytoalexins, which are hydroxycinnamic acid amides with anthranilates, have been extensively studied in the interaction with crown rust fungus (

; 

). We previously showed that the dimer of serotonin and 3-(2-aminoethyl)-3-hydroxyindolin-2-one were induced in barley (

Hordeum vulgare

) leaves infected by 

Bipolaris sorokiniana

, the causal agent of spot blotch of the 
Poaceae
plants, and proposed that they serve as phytoalexins in barley (

). However, accumulation of phytoalexins has not been reported in wheat (

Triticum aestivum

).

Phenylamides are amide compounds of hydroxycinnamic or benzoic acids with biogenic amines, which function in plant defense responses. Representative hydroxycinnamic acids composing phenylamides are cinnamic (Cin), 
p
-coumaric (Cou), caffeic (Caf), ferulic (Fer), and benzoic (
Ben
) acids, while amines parts were derived from tryptamine (Try), serotonin (Ser), tyramine (Tyr), agmatine (Agm), and putrescine (Put). Herein, we refer to specific phenylamides using combined abbreviations of the acid parts and amines, e.g. CinTry (cinnamoyltryptamine). Induced phenylamide accumulation has been reported in a wide range of plant species. In rice, infection by the brown spot fungus (

Cochliobolus miyabeanus

) induced the accumulation of FerTry, CouSer, and FerSer, together with Ser (

). In addition, rice leaves irradiated with ultraviolet (UV) light accumulate CinTry, CinTyr, CouSer, and BenTry (

, 

). In barley, 

reported the induced accumulation of CouAgm in methyl jasmonate (MeJA)-treated leaves. Similarly, 

reported the accumulation of CouPut and Cou-3-hydroxy-Put, as well as CouAgm, in barley leaves treated with jasmonic acid (
JA
). In oats, avenanthramides, which are phytoalexins, are hydroxycinnamic acid amides with anthranilic acids (

).

In wheat, benzoxazinoids (Bxs) are the representative defensive specialized metabolites (

, 

; 

). The major Bxs, 2,4-dihydroxy-1,4-benzoxazin-3-one (DIBOA) and its 7- methoxy derivative (DIMBOA), are constitutively stored in vacuoles as glucosides (DIBOA-Glc and DIMBOA-Glc). Because of their anti-aphid, antimicrobial, and phytotoxic activities, Bxs are thought to function in the defense against various biological stresses (

; 

; 

, 

; 

; 

). Conversely, reports on inducible specialized metabolites in wheat are limited. From a metabolic analysis, 

found the differential accumulation of metabolites in rachis and spikelets of near isogenic wheat lines with resistant or susceptible alleles of 
Fhb1
upon 

Fusarium graminearum

infection. Phenolics, lignans, hydroxycinnamic acid amides (phenylamides), flavonoids, compounds related to signaling molecules, terpenoids, indole alkaloids, and compounds related to methionine biosynthesis were suggested to be involved in 
Fhb1
mediated resistance against 

F. graminearum

. Those authors suggested that cell-wall thickening due to the deposition of hydroxycinnamic acid amides and flavonoids was the potential resistance mechanism.

